The Role of Context in Memory Storage and Retrieval​

Lea Lai, Indiana University​

Richard Shiffrin, Indiana University​

​

ASIC 2024​

Press F2 to Leave.

  • •Context plays a fundamental role in theories of memory storage and retrieval.​

  • •​

  • •What is context? How is it different than content?​

​

  • •Content:​

  • •​

  • •When an event is stored in memory some of the information is called ‘content’ and refers to information that distinguishes this event from other similar events that may have occurred in the same setting. Thus during study of a list of words one might encounter “TABLE” and store the visual form, the spelling and the meaning of this word. This content information distinguishes this work from another word studied on the same list, “BOOK”. ​

  • •​

  • •Both were studied in the same ‘context’.​

  • •Context:​

  • •​

  • •An event stored in memory also includes information about the context in which the event occurs. Thus during study of TABLE the memory stored can include information about the room in which the list was presented, the equipment, the weather, one’s mood, one’s bodily feelings and reactions, any sounds at the time, any other people nearby, and much more along these lines.​

  • •Context is critical to enable one to focus retrieval upon events of interest (event storage and retrieval is also called episodic memory). ​

  • •​

  • •E.g. if you are asked to recognize whether the word TABLE had been on the list just presented, it is context that will enable you to focus retrieval on the recent occurrence of TABLE rather than the millions of other lifetime events containing that word.​

  • •​

  • •Context is generally assumed to change gradually as time passes (e.g. Mensink & Raaijmakers, 1988).​

  • •A few things we know about context from laboratory experiments:​

  • •​

  • •It changes little during study of a list of items, but changes between list study and test. Testing changes context more than study.​

  • •​

  • •Context is usually stored automatically for a second or two and additional study time is spent on storing content (like meaning): (Malmberg & Shiffrin, 2005). ​

  • •​

  • •Context may be stored in a way that integrates it with content, or separately from content (Murnane, Phelps & Malmberg 1999).​

  • •In most memory studies memory retrieval is probed with current context at the time of test. This focuses retrieval on recent events.​

  • •​

  • •If one desires to retrieve events in the past, can this be facilitated by reconstructing the context at the time of storage? There is not much research, but Bauml and colleagues have recently published such evidence (e.g. Bauml & Trissl, 2022).​

  • •Context is seldom varied in memory experiments.​

  • •​

  • •Occasionally attempts are made to do so, for example by changing the room in which events are studied to a different room for testing.​

  • •​

  • •These attempts generally produce very small effects, probably because the aspect of context manipulated is just one of hundreds of elements that make up context. ​

  • •​

  • •Models of context are very primitive, generally assuming little more than the fact that context changes over time and in different settings. ​

  • •The present study was therefore designed to shed light on context and hopefully lead to a detailed model of its role in memory.​

  • •​

  • •Participants in Study 1 were tested with recognition for pictures.​

  • •​

  • •Participants in one Study 2 were tested with cued recall for words.​

  • •​

  • •The designs were similar.​

  • •​

  • •Participants studied a list of 20 items (pictures or words) and were then tested for memory of items on that list only. They saw 10 lists in all.​

  • •​

  • •In both studies the accuracy of responses and the time to respond were recorded and analyzed.​

  • •​

  • •​

  • •Then there was a final test for memory for any item seen in the first ten lists. There were three types of final tests:​

  • •​

  • •Random (R): Items seen in the first part of the study were tested in random order, and no information was provided about where in the session an item might have appeared.​

  • •​

  • •Backward (B): Items seen in the first ten lists were tested in backward order of the lists (i.e. list ten first, then list nine, etc) and participants were told for each test which list might have contained the item. ​

  • •​

  • •Forward (F): Items seen in the first ten lists were tested in forward order of the lists (i.e. list one first, then list two, etc) and participants were told for each test which list might have contained the item. ​

  • •Study 1: Recognition​

  • •​

  • •After each list (or 20 pictures) ten studied pictures (targets, or OLD) were mixed with ten pictures never before seen in the study (foils, or NEW). Subjects gave an OLD/NEW response. ​

  • •​

  • •Final testing: All pictures studied and all foils tested in the first part of the study (now targets, to be called OLD) were mixed with an equal number of never seen pictures (foils, to be called NEW). ​

  • •Study 2: Cued recall:​

  • •​

  • •After each list of 20 words, 10 words were cued with the first two letters. The participants typed an entire word when they thought they recalled a word from that list starting with those letters. ​

  • •​

  • •Final testing: Every word studied was cued with the first two letters. As was the case for recognition, there were three groups: final testing in random, backward, or forward order. ​

  • •The goal of these studies was twofold:​

​

Obtain data that would enable development of a detailed model of the way context operates in memory studies.​

​

Assess the possibility that knowledge of what earlier list was being tested would enable the probe of memory to use context appropriate for that list, producing different and better retrieval than the random condition.​

  • •Some of the major findings:​
